    <etym xml:lang="ru">Из <mentioned xml:lang=""
            ><lang/><w>ādam</w><gloss><q>человек</q></gloss></mentioned>. Слово распространено по
        всему Кавказу: <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/><w>adamiani</w></mentioned>, <mentioned
            xml:lang="dar"><lang/><w>adam</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="dar"
            ><w>adamili</w></mentioned>, , <mentioned xml:lang="lbe"
            ><lang/><w>adamina</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="av"
            ><lang/><w>ʽadam</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="av"><w>ʽadan</w></mentioned>,
            <mentioned xml:lang=""><lang/><w>adam</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang=""
                ><lang/><w>adam</w></mentioned>. Ср. также: <mentioned xml:lang="sog"
                ><lang/><w>ādam</w></mentioned> (<bibl><author>Залеман</author><ref
                target="#ref_ИАН"/><biblScope>1907, стр. 537</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned
            xml:lang="yai"><lang/><w>ādam</w><gloss><q>человек</q></gloss></mentioned><mentioned
            xml:lang="yai"><w/><gloss><q>люди</q></gloss></mentioned>, . В осетинском неоформленное
        %iadæm%i имеет значение не индивида, а коллектива: ‘люди’, ‘народ’, и уже отсюда, с помощью
        суффикса %i-ag%i, образовано понятие ‘человек’; аналогичную картину мы находим в племенных
        названиях: <ref type="xr" target="#entry_tætær"/> ‘татары’ — <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_tætæjrag"/> ‘татарин’, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_g0yrʒy"/> ‘грузины’
        — <ref type="xr" target="#entry_g0yrʒiag"/> ‘грузин’, и т. п.; объясняется это, несомненно,
        тем, что в осознании людей той эпохи, которую отражает в данном случае осетинский язык,
        понятие коллектива было первичным, а понятие индивида — вторичным.%n<bibl><ref
                target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."/><biblScope>9. — </biblScope></bibl><bibl><ref
                target="#ref_Hübschmann._Oss."/><biblScope>119.</biblScope></bibl></etym>
    <etym xml:lang="en">From <mentioned xml:lang=""><lang/><w>ādam</w><gloss><q>person, human
                    being</q></gloss></mentioned>. The word is widespread all across the Caucasus:
            <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/><w>adamiani</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="dar"
                ><lang/><w>adam</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="dar"><w>adamini</w></mentioned>,
        , <mentioned xml:lang="lbe"><lang/><w>adamina</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="av"
                ><lang/><w>ʽadam</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="av"><w>ʽadan</w></mentioned>,
            <mentioned xml:lang=""><lang/><w>adam</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang=""
                ><lang/><w>adam</w></mentioned>. Compare <mentioned xml:lang="sog"
                ><lang/><w>ādam</w></mentioned> (<bibl><ref target="#ref_Залеман._Ягн."
                /><biblScope>IAN 1907, p. 537</biblScope></bibl>) <mentioned xml:lang="yai"
                ><lang/><w>ādam</w><gloss><q>person, people</q></gloss></mentioned>. In Ossetic
        %iadæm%i without suffixation refers not to an individual, but to a group: ‘people’,
        ‘nation’. The word for ‘person’ is derived from this root using the suffix %i-ag%i. A
        similar situation is observed for tribal or national names: <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_tætær"/> ‘the Tatars’ — <ref type="xr" target="#entry_tætæjrag"/> ‘a
        Tatar’, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_g0yrʒ"/> ‘the Georgians’ — <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_g0yrʒiag"/> ‘a Georgian’, etc. The explanation for this is surely that in
        the conscience of the people of earlier times, reflected here in the Ossetic language, the
        concept of a group was primary, and the concept of an individual was secondary.%n<bibl><ref
                target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."/><biblScope>9.</biblScope></bibl> — <bibl><ref
                target="#ref_Hübschmann._Oss."/><biblScope>119.</biblScope></bibl></etym>
